rComments: Not always clear during lecture, but is very willing to explain after class and during office hours (very accessible). Cares a lot about whether students are understanding material and does great test / exam reviews.

Hands down the best math instructor I've ever had, he'll you exactly what to focus on and study for evaluations. The amount of hours he puts in after class is unreal, I have not seen anyone as dedicated to helping students as Justin Martel. His lectures are very entertaining and you will not get bored whatsoever. Very unfortunate that he's leaving.

He is an amazing Professor who will give in so much of his time to make students understand and will not stop until they understand. He usually stays back after classes, before classes and his office hours are always very helpful since he goes into more depth. He's really funny and the tophat questions were interesting.

He tries his best but sometimes he doesn't explain a topic very well. But he's super nice and genuinely does his best to teach, and he really does seem to care about his students. His stares ARE intimidating but he doesn't do that on purpose, and while the stuff he teaches isn't super related to the dept-wide test sometimes, the tests are bs anyway
He explains most math problems well and theres in class participation mark which is easy to get.

Not good at explaining. Since he's a grad student he seems like he doesn't know how to teach and doesn't have much experience teaching. The term test was nothing like the questions which he explained in class. He skimmed over the topics and the test was unexpected because he didn't prepare us for it properly. If you have him as a prof, good luck

He's an okay prof. He is kind of intimidating (kinda scared when i sit in the front row because he just stares). Doesn't really explain concepts just does questions and says he talks too much when he can't properly explain it. When he gives up, its top hat time
